Plot One

The first plot created is to show the allocations of Australian federal budget by sector for the financial years between 2017-2018 and 2021-2022.

# Load data
payments_sector <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/Total_payments_for_specific_purposes_by_sector-2017-18-to-2021-22.csv")
payments_sector <- as.data.frame(payments_sector)

# Update column names
colnames(payments_sector) <- c("Sector", "2017-18", "2018-19", "2019-20", "2020-21", "2021-22")

# Remove the total payments row (as we are only interested in the sectors)
payments_sector <- payments_sector[payments_sector$Sector != "Total payments for specific purposes", ]

# Transpose the dataset to long format
payments_sector_long <- pivot_longer(payments_sector,
                                     cols = c("2017-18", "2018-19",
                                         "2019-20", "2020-21", "2021-22"),
                                     names_to = "Year",
                                     values_to = "Payments($million)")

#head(payments_sector_long)

# The data wrangling code below is for calculating the CPI-adjustment payments
CPI <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/All_groups_CPI_weighted_average_of_eight_capital_cities.csv")
CPI_subset <- subset(CPI, Year %in% c(2017, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021))

CPI_subset2 <- cbind(c("2021-22", "2020-21", "2019-20",
                       "2018-19", "2017-18"), 
                     CPI_subset$X31.December)
CPI_subset2 <- as.data.frame(CPI_subset2)
colnames(CPI_subset2) <- c("Year", "CPI")
CPI_subset2$CPI <- as.numeric(CPI_subset2$CPI)

# Join payments_sector_long with CPI_subset2
payments_sector_long_adjusted <- inner_join(payments_sector_long, CPI_subset2, by = "Year")

# Add a column to hold CPI-adjusted payments
payments_sector_long_adjusted$`Payment_Adjusted($million)` <- round(payments_sector_long_adjusted$`Payments($million)` / payments_sector_long_adjusted$CPI * 100, 2)
# Plot a heatmap to visualise the payments by sector
heatmap1 <- ggplot(payments_sector_long, aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Sector)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = `Payments($million)`)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = `Payments($million)`)) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "#023858",
                        name = "Payments\n($million)") +
  labs(title = "Australian Federal Budget Allocations - Payments by Sector",
       subtitle = "2017-2018 to 2021-2022",
       x = "Year", y = "Sector") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#969696"))



# Create another heatmap based on CPI-adjusted payments
heatmap2 <- ggplot(payments_sector_long_adjusted,
       aes(x = as.factor(Year), y = Sector)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = `Payment_Adjusted($million)`)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = `Payment_Adjusted($million)`)) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "#023858",
                        name = "CPI Adjusted\nPayments\n($million)") +
  labs(title = "Australian Federal Budget Allocations - CPI Adjusted Payments by Sector",
       subtitle = "2017-2018 to 2021-2022",
       x = "Year", y = "Sector") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 9),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#969696"))

grid.arrange(heatmap1, heatmap2, ncol = 1)

Plot two

# Load data
payments_state_21_22 <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/2021-22_StateBreakdown_BySector.csv")
payments_state_20_21 <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/2020-21_StateBreakdown_BySector.csv")
payments_state_19_20 <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/2019-20_StateBreakdown_BySector.csv")
payments_state_18_19 <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/2018-19_StateBreakdown_BySector.csv")
payments_state_17_18 <- read.csv("E:/Semester 2/MXB262/Assessment/FinalProject/Data/2017-18_StateBreakdown_BySector.csv")

columns_to_round <- c(2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9)

# Round up the values in the selected columns and add a year column
payments_state_21_22[columns_to_round] <- round(payments_state_21_22[columns_to_round])
payments_state_21_22$Year <- rep('2021-22', times = nrow(payments_state_21_22))

payments_state_20_21[columns_to_round] <- round(payments_state_20_21[columns_to_round])
payments_state_20_21$Year <- rep('2020-21', times = nrow(payments_state_20_21))

payments_state_19_20[columns_to_round] <- round(payments_state_19_20[columns_to_round])
payments_state_19_20$Year <- rep('2019-20', times = nrow(payments_state_19_20))

payments_state_18_19[columns_to_round] <- round(payments_state_18_19[columns_to_round])
payments_state_18_19$Year <- rep('2018-19', times = nrow(payments_state_18_19))

payments_state_17_18[columns_to_round] <- round(payments_state_17_18[columns_to_round])
payments_state_17_18$Year <- rep('2017-18', times = nrow(payments_state_17_18))

# Create a data frame to calculate the average payments paid to each state over the period
payments_state_year <- rbind(payments_state_21_22[nrow(payments_state_21_22), ],
                payments_state_20_21[nrow(payments_state_20_21), ],
                payments_state_19_20[nrow(payments_state_19_20), ],
                payments_state_18_19[nrow(payments_state_18_19), ],
                payments_state_17_18[nrow(payments_state_17_18), ])

# Calculate the average payments each state received over the period
average_payments <- round(colMeans(payments_state_year[2:9]))

# Getting the map geometry data and putting it into a new object
sf_au <- ozmap("states")

# Add average payments of each state as another column to sf_au
sf_au$avgpayments <- c(average_payments[1], average_payments[2],
average_payments[3], average_payments[5],
average_payments[4], average_payments[6],
average_payments[8], average_payments[7], NA)

# Calculate the centroids of each state polygon
sf_au <- cbind(sf_au, st_coordinates(st_centroid(sf_au)))
## Warning: st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over geometries
ggplot(data = sf_au, aes(fill = avgpayments)) +
  geom_sf() +
  geom_text(aes(X, Y, label = avgpayments), size = 4, face = "bold", color = "#ef6548") +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "#023858",
                        name = "Payments") +
  labs(title = "Federal Government's Payments to States for Specific Purposes",
       subtitle = "2021-2022") +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        axis.text = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank())
## Warning in geom_text(aes(X, Y, label = avgpayments), size = 4, face = "bold", :
## Ignoring unknown parameters: `face`

Plot three

# Filter to only retrieve data from selected states
payments_state_year_selected <- payments_state_year[, c("NSW", "VIC","QLD", "Year")]

# Transpose to long format
payments_states_long <- pivot_longer(payments_state_year_selected,
                                     cols = c("NSW", "VIC","QLD"),
                                     names_to = "State",
                                     values_to = "Payments($million)")

# Join payments_states_long with CPI_subset2
payments_states_long_adjusted <- left_join(payments_states_long, CPI_subset2, by = "Year")

# Add a column to hold CPI-adjusted payments
payments_states_long_adjusted$`Payments_Adjusted($million)` <- round(payments_states_long_adjusted$`Payments($million)` / payments_states_long_adjusted$CPI * 100, 2)
# Create a stacked line plot
# Set order of factor levels
payments_states_long_adjusted$State <- factor(payments_states_long_adjusted$State,
levels = c("NSW", "VIC", "QLD"))

line_plot1 <- ggplot(payments_states_long_adjusted, aes(Year, `Payments($million)`)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = State, group = State), size = 1.6) +
  geom_point(
    aes(fill = State), 
    size = 3.6, 
    pch = 21, # Type of point that allows us to have both color (border) and fill.
    color = "white", 
    stroke = 1 # The width of the border, i.e. stroke.
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#2b8cbe", "#31a354", "#e34a33")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#2b8cbe", "#31a354", "#e34a33")) +
  labs(title = "Payments to Selected States for Specific Purposes",
       subtitle = "2017-2018 to 2021-2022") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "grey"),
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_line(colour = "grey"),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  geom_text(aes(x = 5, y = 17300, label = "NSW"), 
            color = "#2b8cbe", size = 4, vjust = -0.5) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 5, y = 14300, label = "VIC"), 
            color = "#31a354", size = 4, vjust = -0.5) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 5, y = 13600, label = "QLD"), 
            color = "#e34a33", size = 4, vjust = -0.5)

                                              payments_states_long_adjusted$State == "NSW", "Payments_Adjusted($million)"][1,1])


line_plot2 <- ggplot(payments_states_long_adjusted, aes(Year, `Payments_Adjusted($million)`)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = State, group = State), size = 1.6) +
  geom_point(
    aes(fill = State), 
    size = 3.6, 
    pch = 21, # Type of point that allows us to have both color (border) and fill.
    color = "white", 
    stroke = 1 # The width of the border, i.e. stroke.
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#2b8cbe", "#31a354", "#e34a33")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#2b8cbe", "#31a354", "#e34a33")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),

        legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = bquote(bold("CPI-Adjusted") ~ "Payments to Selected States for Specific Purposes"),

            color = "#e34a33", size = 4, vjust = -0.5) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 4, y = 15000, label = "NSW is getting less money!"),
